consider why the twenty-first century media landscape is so haunted by the ghosts of these traditional figures that feminism otherwise laid to rest. Why, over fifty years since Betty Friedan’s critique, does the feminine mystique exert such a strong spectral presence, and how has it been reimagined to speak to the concerns of a postfeminist audience? To answer these questions, Munford and Waters draw from a rich array of examples from contemporary film, fiction, music, and television, from the shadowy cityscapes of Homeland to the haunted houses of American Horror Story. Alongside this comprehensive analysis of today’s popular culture, they offer a vivid portrait of feminism’s social and intellectual history, as well as an innovative application of Jacques Derrida’s theories of “hauntology.” Feminism and Popular Culture thus not only considers how contemporary media is being visited by the ghosts of feminism’s past, it raises vital questions about what this means for feminism’s future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFeminism and mass media. 0aFeminist theory. 0aWomen in popular culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apostfeminist phenomena.1 aWaters, Melanie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWhelehan, Imelda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhelehan, Imelda.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356742640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813567426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813567426/original  a978-3-11-066615-1  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles